# Points Harvest — Automate Your Bing Rewards

Points Harvest is a free, open-source Chrome extension that automatically completes your daily Bing Rewards searches, Explore activities, Daily Set tiles, and More Activities tiles — minimal interaction required.

Following Microsoft's 2026 Rewards overhaul, Gold-tier users in the United States can potentially earn around **3,000 points per month** (~$36/year) through the extension alone. See the full breakdown: {{ site.baseUrl }}/blog/maximum-rewards-points.md

- Download the latest release ({{ site.extensionVersion }}): {{ site.downloadUrl }}
- View the source on GitHub: {{ site.githubUrl }}

Not affiliated with or endorsed by Microsoft.

## Features

- **Explore on Bing Activities** — Detects and completes all your "Search on Bing" activity cards, mapping each to the right query automatically.
- **Daily Set Tiles** — Opens daily set activities. Handles simple ones automatically; surfaces quizzes and polls so you can complete them.
- **PC Search Farming** — After activities are done, farms remaining PC searches until the daily cap, with points earning verification.
- **More Activities** — Completes "More Activities" tiles automatically — opens each tile's search page, dwells, and validates. Skips puzzles, quizzes, and install prompts.
- **Hands-on When It Matters** — Quizzes, polls, and puzzles are surfaced for you to complete manually — the extension handles everything else automatically.

## See it in action

Hit Start and walk away. Points Harvest works through warm-up searches, Explore on Bing activities, Daily Sets, More Activities, and PC search farming — all in sequence, all on its own. Quizzes and polls are surfaced for you to complete; everything else is hands-free.

Every phase shows live progress, point earnings, and activity counts so you always know exactly where a run stands.

## Installation

1. **Download the latest release.** Download {{ site.downloadUrl }} and extract it.
2. **Load into Chrome.** Navigate to `chrome://extensions`, enable **Developer mode** (top right), then click **Load unpacked** and select the extracted folder.
3. **Run it.** Open https://rewards.bing.com, make sure you're signed into your Microsoft account, then click the Points Harvest icon in Chrome and hit **Run today's searches**.

First time? Read the full getting started guide for detailed instructions, pop-up permissions setup, and tips: {{ site.baseUrl }}/blog/getting-started.md

## FAQ

**Is this an official Microsoft or Bing extension?**
No. Points Harvest is an independent tool with no affiliation with Microsoft, Bing, or the Rewards program. It is not endorsed, authorized, or supported by Microsoft in any way.

**Will my Bing account get banned?**
There is a risk — Microsoft's Rewards Terms of Service prohibit automated point collection. Points Harvest is transparent about this: the extension shows a warning on first launch. It uses human-like randomized timing and does not spoof anything, but no tool can guarantee your account is safe. Use it at your own discretion.

**Is it really free and open-source? Any catch?**
Yes, completely free and open-source ({{ site.githubUrl }}). No account, no login, no subscription. The source code is publicly available on GitHub — you can inspect exactly what the extension does. It runs entirely on your device with no tracking or analytics of any kind.

**How many points can I earn per day?**
Points Harvest automates four phases each run: Explore on Bing activity cards, Daily Set tiles, More Activities tiles, and PC search farming up to your daily cap. Following Microsoft's 2026 Rewards overhaul, Gold-tier users in the United States can potentially earn around 3,000 points per month through the extension alone. Full breakdown: {{ site.baseUrl }}/blog/maximum-rewards-points.md

**Does it need my Microsoft password?**
No. Points Harvest never asks for or stores your credentials. It operates entirely through your already-signed-in Chrome session on rewards.bing.com and bing.com — the same way you'd use those sites normally.

**Does it work in Edge or Firefox?**
Other Chromium-based browsers like Brave, Opera, and Vivaldi support unpacked extensions the same way Chrome does. Edge is more complex — it is primarily designed to install extensions from the Chrome Web Store rather than loading them unpacked. Firefox is not supported; it uses a different extension format.
